@node not15 "AMIGA SHOW ANALYSIS BY CORINNA COHN"
                      AMIGA SHOW ANALYSIS BY CORINNA COHN
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This report has been written by Corinna Cohn (lazuli42@yahoo.com).

Hello,

I spent Saturday, April 1st and Sundary, April 2nd in St. Louis as the Amiga 2k
show. Following are some of the rumours, some of the news, and some of my
impressions.

                                   The Crowd:

As usual for the St. Louis show, on the morning of the first day the line of
visitors extended from the entry doors back to the lobby of the hotel. Nearly
everyone, visitor and vendor alike, was wearing some sort of Amiga pagentry.

There was a carefully optimistic attitude amongst the attendees. Naturally,
everyone is impatient and wants to have a new Amiga in their hands, but with so
many false starts in the past it seems that the idea is to hope for the best but
expect the worst. What are Amiga's plans? I'll explain below.

This is the fourth year of the St. Louis show, and I've attended them all. The
faces in the crowds are nearly all familiar to me. Attendence has slowly
declined over those years, but I think this is because there is no new system to
purchase. Also, the turnout of developers, while not necessarily decreasing, is
certainly not increasing and there isn't much new to see.

I heard other people remark that they saw some new faces. Hopefully, if more
good news keeps coming from Amiga then we'll see new crowds at the show next
year.

                                  The Vendors:

The old World of Amiga shows used to inspire vendors to the heights of
decorative creativity as they competed for the attention and cash of show goers.
Nowaday it's rare to find a festively designed booth, but some vendors still try
to dress up a little bit. Whereas the old big shows were semi-formals, this show
was casual.

My favourite part of the shows has always been the developers' displays. It's
fun to see the latest and greatest release of my preferred programs, or to see
what new applications are out. With the slowdown of the marketplace, there was
little new to see. Here's is a list of products that left an impression on me:

   - Hyperion had a number of games on display including Heretic II, Wipeout
     2097, and Shogo. All of the games were running on a 233Mhz PPC. Heretic II
     looked choppy and pixelated, and Shogo was only available as a demo, but
     Wipeout 2097 looked very smooth. The Amiga version was absolutely better
     than the Playstation version--it looked as good as any current PC game.

   - Weemsware was demonstrating a program which animated a mouth on a cartoon
     figure which used the Amiga translator.device for cues on which shape the
     mouth should be in. The end result is that the figure had appropriate
     mouth movements for the words that it was pronouncing. The program also
     included some other clever features such as being able to easily lip-synch
     with a sound file.

   - Paul Nolan was demonstrating Photogenics 4 on a Linux laptop. For anyone
     familiar with The Gimp, let me say that Photogenics makes that program
     look like an amateurish college project. Photogenics is fast and polished
     with a consistant interface. The GUI is built from a toolkit of Paul's own
     design, and while sometimes a little counter-intuitive (for instance, the
     tabbed panes are vertical instead of horizontal and automatically switch
     when the mouse moves over them), is cetainly much better than the one used
     for The Gimp. I was curious as to why Paul was using a PC instead of an
     Amiga for his demonstration. Apparently his Amiga was damaged right before
     the show, but he assured me that the two programs were nearly identical.
     For those Linux geeks, keep an eye out on the toolkit, which might be
     released as Open Source in the future.

   - Nova Design has a new product called Millennium which is a collection of
     third party tools, utilities, graphics, and plug-ins for the Videto
     Toaster and the Flyer. Nova Design did not have this collection available
     for demonstration because of the absence of a Toaster. Kermit Woodall
     mentioned that sales have been good for the product.

   - SoftLogik showed up after a two year hiatus with their new Pagestream 4.0.
     The demonstration machine didn't seem to have a graphics card which is too
     bad because this is a program that needs to be run in high-res (1024x768)
     mode to take full advantage of it. I spoke to Daren, the demonstrator, and
     asked about the stability of the different versions. The MacOS and Amiga
     versions are quite stable, but the Windows version continues to have a
     printing bug that they are busily trying to repair.

Although there were other developers, unfortunately I didn't take the time to
see what their products did. No slight is intended against these fine folks who
are supporting the market with their blood, sweat and tears.

Oh, finally I guess I should mention that Anti-Gravity was showing the BoXeR
there in an acrylic case. The motherboard is ATX form factor. Two things struck
me about the design: There are 3 DIMM slots, but only two are for RAM expansion.
The last is intended to be the connector for a PPC card. The other thing that
struck me was that stereo out ports were positioned in a spot that you'd have to
knock out of an ATX case, and that there were no joystick ports. The
Anti-Gravity representitive suggested using a USB joystick, but I wonder if this
would work with older games? A manufacturing plant in California has been
selected for the production of this board, and they expect to be shipping in
about two months.

                                  The Banquet:

I hate mushrooms. Actually, I also hate banquet dining. I even hate the way
banquet is spelled. The only banquet that I ever really enjoyed was the first
one at the Sacramento show which was served buffet style.

Anyway, after dinner, and after our crunchy ice-cream was served (yech), Bill
McEwen got up to present his demonstration. Bill faced the crowd wielding a
six-pack of Diet Coke and a slick Scala slideshow. After presenting Bob Scharp
and his wife Dianna personallized Amiga bomber jackets for all of their hard
work on the show, and after inviting the crowd to take a commemerative Amiga
tee-shirt, Bill got down to the nitty-gritty.

The first part of the presentation was a history of the new Amiga. Bill spoke
about being fired from Amiga (which is not quite true since he was a contractor,
not an employee), and went on to show that living well is the best revenge. Some
pictures of the new Amiga offices and the view from said offices brought home
the point that Amiga has money, and moreever, intends to make money.

The presentation continued with a recap of what they've done in their first
three months of work. I noted the strong similarities of Bill's speech and the
one given by Jim Callos last year at the same event. Sometimes, Bill even used
the exact same phrases. More on this in a bit. Amiga's partnership with Tao
seems to be the most important part of Amiga's new strategy. Tao is serving a
similar purpose that QNX was originally going to by providing the underpinnings
for the Amiga interface.

Bill continued on, talking about the importance of strategic partnerships, and
dropped such names as Sony, JVC, and Motorolla. What is the relationship between
these companies and Amiga? Well, apparently these companies are trying to come
together to make a standard for a consumer-device operating system, and Amiga
hopes to bridge the gaps between these different companies goals. Here is my
understanding: The Amiga environment (or OE, operating environment per Jim
Collas) will sit on top of Taos' virtual machine, which can sit on top of
another operating system, such as Linux. This means that no matter the operating
system, Amiga+Tao can be the interface for both the user and applications. Will
this work? Who knows? But I'm interested in seeing what happens.

Mr. McEwen also talked about how Amiga is receiving support from two different
Linux companies, Red Hat and Corel. Bill talked about how these companies are
excited to be working with Amiga, but the slides he showed which quoted both Bob
Young and Michael Cowpland seemed to indicate only that the companies were happy
to hear that Amiga wanted to work with them.

After this segment, Bill smeared the work Gateway-Amiga did on case designs
(rumour has it they payed 1.6 MILLION dollars on case design), and then bragged
that he had some designs by Disney animators. He then went on to show about a
dozen slides showing concept towers, desktops, game consoles, and servers. Some
people may have enjoyed these concepts, but my opionion is that only people who
are qualified and experienced in consumer product design should attempt such
work. The designs were either ugly, impractacle, impossible, or all three.
Perhaps Bill will put some pictures on the Amiga web page so that you all can
draw your own conclusions.

There was a brief demonstration of the Tao technology. The Tao was running as a
virtual OS on top of Linux. The Tao window looked exactly like something from
AmigaOS 3.1, but this is fairly easy to do with any system. They demonstrated
the speed of the Tao Java Virtual Machine by opening several applets at the same
time. I'd like to point out that when you load an applet locally, it will run
faster than one that is downloaded because Java doesn't have to make as many
security checks. They had an updated version of the Boing demo, with the
enhancement of being able to actually pick up the ball with the pointer and
throw it around the screen to have it bounce off of things. Other applets
included video filters that could be placed over other windows to do things such
as increase the brightness, apply a sepia tone, or display the window with false
colour.

The presentation concluded after Bill presented the rest of the Amiga team with
similar jackets that the Scharps received earlier in the evening.

                  My Impressions of the Banquet Presentation:

All in all, I was dissatisfied with the presentation. The first segment seemed
to be a combination of Mr. McEwen rubbing Gateway's nose into the dirt, and Mr.
McEwen talking about what an amazing guy Fleecy Moss is (my opinions of Fleecy
are well known, but I'll have more on that anon). I think that this part of the
presentation could have been done without very easily. All it did was negatively
impact my opinion of Bill McEwen's professionalism.

The partnerships that Mr. McEwen got so excited about worked out like this:
Amiga is a partner with Tao, Tao is a partner with some other companies, those
companies have a partnership with JVC, Sony, etc... Aparently this may have been
enough for Amiga to get meetings with those companies, but this seems a lot like
a friend of a friend of a friend relationship. I thought Bill misrepresented the
relationship between the Linux companies and Amiga. Does Red Hat and Corel want
to work with Amiga? Or are they just happy that Amiga wants to work with them? I
asked Bill McEwen to clarify this later in the evening, which I'll elaborate on
below.

The case designs that Bill presented were gruesome. One after the other, it was
like having to see slides of acid burn victims. The tower case looked like it
was reflected in a fun-house mirror. The game consoles looked like bubbling
plastic blisters, or like camping lanterns, depending on the design. The servers
looked like toilets with exhaust pipes. I don't know why Bill was so proud of
these designs. There are better concepts on Aminet for new Amigas. Hell, the
vacuum-look-alike that Escom designed looked better. The A600 looked better.

I left the presentation quite pissed off.

                           My Talk With Bill McEwen:

Later on in the evening I was able to confront Mr. McEwen about his
presentation. He was open and interested in my opinions, and I'm grateful for
the opportunity of being able to share them with him. I listed several of the
issues I had, and he responded.

In the first case, I told him that I thought his speech sounded too much like
Jim Collas' from last year, and that aside from the Tao demonstration, it was
mostly fluff. Bill said that sounded right, considering that he wrote Jim's
speech from last year. I tried to point out that it was irrelevant that he wrote
it because the end effect was him sounding like he was recycling Jim's platform.
Well... actually they are recycling Amiga's former plans, but with some small
differences.

Secondly, I told him I was concerned that Amiga's level of professionalism was
not high enough to inspire confidence. This mostly goes back to my problems with
Fleecy as a leader (such as joking about bestiality during an interview), and
Bill's continual thumb-nosing at Gateway. I feel like I'd be betraying a
confidence to mention too much here, but I'll say that he addressed my concern
and I'm looking forward to seeing an improvement from Amiga in the future.

Third, I brought of the case designs that he showed off, and in response he told
me that Amiga, outside of the developer box and the perhaps the first consumer
machine, had no plans of selling their own hardware. It was confusing why he
would even show off designs then if they didn't intend on entering those markets
with their own products. I told him that he left the impression that they were
going to make those products, and he said that he would try to clarify better
what Amiga's plans are concerning hardware.

Finally, I brought up my problems with his mentioning the Linux companies as
partners. I asked why Red Hat or Corel would abandon KDE or Gnome in favour of
the Amiga system and he explained that Amiga was only going to use the Linux
kernal. It wouldn't make sense to team up with the two players if they were just
using the Linux kernal, so I think two things might be going on here: 1) Amiga
is trying to gain attention by playing off the Linux name. 2) Red Hat and Corel
might try to enter the consumer device market with the Amiga interface.

                         My Interview With Fleecy Moss:

Would you believe how that no fewer than three people who read my initial
criticism of Fleecy on the MooBunny actually approached me at the show to thank
me for it? "Arexx" Aaron Ruscetta convinced me that I should at least be more
open minded towards Fleecy's ideas, so I decided to actually talk to Fleecy.

Fleecy, although very busy Sunday morning, was kind enough to lend me some time.
To avoid being bothered, we snuck back to the pool and grabbed a table with only
two chairs. I explained that I'd been quite critical of him, and that in the
interest of fairness I'd like to get his perspectives. Unfortunately I had no
method of recording the conversation so there won't be any quotes, but I will
paraphrase.

I opened with my charge that he hadn't enough experience to be doing the work he
was. I asked him to explain how any of the jobs he'd worked on before related to
what his responsibilities were now. He told me that he'd consulted as a project
manager on a number of big business projects. He described some of the systems
that they were working on, what the end goal was, and how they achieved the
goals. Fleecy has been accused of being a jargon-slinger in the past, and I can
verify that it's true, but he knows what it all means even if he uses it too
much.

I remain unconvinced that the projects that he worked on before really prepared
him for what he's doing now, but I now have a better idea of what he's
accomplished in the past. I'd guess that there are 20,000 people in the US right
now that have the same sort of experience. Few of those people are actually
working on operating systems or operating environments, because those kinds of
projects take expertise of the sort that I think Fleecy lacks. We will see what
becomes of his projects. It seems that the partnership with Tao is positive. In
fact, everything we've seen so far are Tao's ideas, not Fleecy's. I'm interested
to see what kind of impact his additions will make.

I brought up the point that all of the community groups that he'd either started
or been a leader in had fallen into shambles. He talked about the politics
behind JMS, the goals of OASYS, and what went wrong with KOSH. He also talked
about his relationships with various people at Amiga. On the later, he actually
went on for quite a while, and from his perspective there is enmity between he
and Alan Havemose, Jeff Schindler and Steve Jones. From the sounds of things,
Fleecy hadn't a good relationship with anyone there except for Bill McEwen,
which explains their current partnership.

Fleecy doesn't have everything it takes to be the leader some people want to be,
and he seems to recognize that. He said he was sorry for all of the cutting
public remarks he'd made about his previous employers, and he was sorry for
launching his attacks from Kosh, which wasn't supposed to have been related. He
said that he'd bothered that so many people seem to blindly follow him. He said
he appreciates constructive criticism.

My opinion of Fleecy has changed a little bit. I no longer think of him as being
out increase his own fame at the expense of the Amiga, but I do think of him as
being a little short-sighted. I still think his ideas are a little strange,
although I no longer rank him with Tim Rue. His concepts are too abstract to try
to go from concept to commercial without plenty of research, but I think he
deserves a chance to do the research. If Fleecy were happy with just doing R&D
for Amiga, I'd be satisfied. If he got out of the spotlight, I'd stop
complaining. If he stops modelling himself as a community leader, I'll no longer
throw stones.

There are two ways people relate to Fleecy. Either they adore him and consider
him to be a visionary, or they oppose him and consider him a faker. How many
ways do people relate to Randall somethingorother, some guy who's one of the big
three Amiga executives but whose last name I can't remember? If Fleecy weren't
jumping out in front of the camera all the time, there'd be no debate about him.

                             Corinna's Rumour Mill:

   - From a room party with some game developers: Some of Amiga's funding is
     coming from Jim Collas.

     I personally disbelieve this rumour. I asked what Fleecy thought of Jim
     Collas, and while he didn't seem to have the same kind of vitriol for him
     as for other former Amiga personel, he wasn't overly enthusiastic.

   - Overheard near Anti-Gravity booth: Anti-Gravity is very pissed off with
     Mick Tinker and they're at the breaking point. They want their BoXeR board
     completed. They've had to go to a number of new investors to keep the
     project going. They're concerned that nobody will buy one without an AGP
     slot.

     I'd say there's a reasonable chance that this is true. I saw Joe Torre
     pointing them to an article in a computer magazine comparing the
     performance of PCI to AGP (for those that are curious, AGP usually doesn't
     make a sizable difference).

   - Overheard after banquet: Fleecy Moss and Bill McEwen have been butting
     heads on issues concerning the direction of Amiga.

     Who knows? In my talk with Bill McEwen he emphasized that he is the leader
     of the company, and he doesn't mind upsetting other people to get things
     done the way he wants them.

   - Overheard Sunday morning: A conglomerate of Japanese and European
     businesses are financing Amiga.

     Yeah, and Microsoft is going to buy out Amiga. They money they have is
     coming from somewhere, but I doubt Amiga even shows up as a blip on
     anyones radar.

That's it folks. I hope you appreciate my news and views.

Corinna Cohn
