@node not21 "OPEN FOUNDATION PROGRESS UPDATE FOR MARCH 2000"
                 OPEN FOUNDATION PROGRESS UPDATE FOR MARCH 2000
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                             Open Amiga Foundation

  Progress Report for March 7th, 2000 by Open Amiga President Steve Crietzman

                          Introduction to this report

It has been some time since our last update to the Amiga community, several
weeks in fact. In this time there has been a huge amount of progress and
activity behind the scenes which has gone unreported.

We must apologise for the long delay between the last progress report on this
one. However, there are good reasons for this.

Please allow us to explain.

It is the policy of the Open Amiga Foundation not to make announcements
prematurely - before we know we can deliver on them - and so we have been
reluctant to discuss what had been happening behind closed doors. Many of our
projects - our negotiations - were at early stages of development, and we were
unsure whether we were able to gain the necessary commitment from various
companies we were negotiating with. It was therefore felt necessary to leave the
negotiations unreported, until a more definite resolution was on the horizon.

However, we felt too long had gone by without an update, and since we are now
fairly optimistic of a satisfactory outcome, we are departing with our usual
policy to give people an idea of what is going on. It must be stressed, however,
that nothing discussed in this progress report is fixed in stone.

The reason this information is being shared early with the community is in the
interests of openess and transparency. The Open Amiga Foundation seeks to be as
open and accessible as possible, and to sync ourselves as closely with Amiga
community opinion as possible.

Our regular reports are created to keep the community up to date on our
progress, and to encourage maximum feedback and paticipation by interested
members of the Amiga community.

So, without further ado, here's what's new since our last progress update.

           Amiga application authors releasing source code under GPL

In the last several weeks, several Amiga applications developers have taken the
plunge and released their applications under liberal open source licenses, such
as the Free Software Foundation's GNU General Public License.

We want to thank the Amiga developers who have taken this bold step.

We especially want to thank Greg Perry and Jonathan Potter of GPSoft, for
releasing the source code to Directory Opus, Douglas McLaughlin for the release
of the strICQ source code under the GPL license, and Manuel Lemos of the BGUI
Development Team for their committment to migrate their development to an
open-source strategy in the near future.

The release of such a rich variety of source code is extremely helpful to those
of us working on creating a free, portable software AmigaOS solution. All code
released under the GPL becomes immediately available to us to utilise directly
within the Open Source AmigaOS project, currently under way at Open Amiga/AROS.

If any developers of Amiga system-level software, such as filing systems, are
reading this progress update, we would request you contribute to the free,
portable AmigaOS project by releasing your source code under the GNU General
Public License, or a similar license. OAF/AROS's AmigaOS project in particular
needs a portable, free filing system. It would help if a developer of a filing
system would release their code under GPL; this would save us valuable time,
effort and energy that could better be spent developing other parts of the OS.
It saves us duplicating work already done by someone else.

             Discussions with Gateway over access to Amiga patents

Critical to creating a convincing copy of the Amiga operating system is access
to the Amiga-related software patents currently held by Gateway. These are
arguably the most important piece of the puzzle, since they are required to
create a convincing AmigaOS clone - many of these patents govern the appearance,
functionality and internal workings of the operating system - such as the famous
"right-mouse button menu" patent.

In recognition of the significant importance of these patents to our cousin
open-source project AROS, the Open Amiga Foundation have been in discussions
with Gateway's attorneys for the past several weeks, and we now believe we are
close to an acceptable working agreement for access to these patents.

If we are successful, we will be able to implement the unique Amiga user
interface design into the open-source AmigaOS/AROS project. AROS will be able to
look, feel, and operate in every important way identically to the existing Amiga
operating system, without violating anyone's patents, trademarks or copyrights.

We will have Gateway's permission to use the patents, we will not utilise any
copyrighted AmigaOS source code as part of the AROS project, and we are hopeful
of reaching agreement with Amiga for the rights to use trademarked Amiga names
within the AROS project.

However, if push comes to shove, we can always relabel parts of the OS that use
trademarked terms, and develop measures to convert existing code to use the new
terms.

              Cooperation with Amiga International and Amiga, Inc.

The Open Amiga Foundation maintains an open line of communication with Mr. Petro
Tyschtschenko of Amiga International. We frequently discuss matters of mutual
interest and concern, and Mr. Tyschtschenko, as an open supporter of our
project, has frequently offered both public and private support for our
activities. We cannot thank Mr. Tyschtschenko enough for his kind support and
encouragement over the past several weeks and months, and we value our continued
discussions and cooperation with Mr. Tyschtschenko greatly. We look forward to
continuing to work with Mr. Tyschtschenko and his team in the future.

Our relationship with Amiga Incorporated in the United States is a little
different, as we are still, I believe, in the process of learning about each
other's projects and plans, and since our discussions with Amiga in the United
States is still in a preliminary stage, it is hard to comment on precisely how
our relationship with Amiga Incorporated will evolve. Nonetheless, we look
forward to building up a more solid working relationship sometime in the future,
when Amiga has more time to work with us on this matter.

Amiga Incorporated have, however, stated their public support for the activities
of the Open Amiga Foundation and AROS, and for that we thank them. We also
appreciated the opportunity to meet with Mr. McEwen and Mr. Moss in Reading,
England earlier this year. It was nice to have an opportunity to meet them and
hear their plans and ideas for the future.

It is our sincerest of desires to work closely and in close cooperation with
Amiga Incorporated on our open source projects.

However, as is clear to anyone who has observed Amiga in recent months, their
primary focus is centered on the development of their symbiotic relationship
with Tao Group, and in producing products and strategies that revolve around
that partnership.

In acknowledgement of Amiga's desire to focus attention in their own
Tao-oriented directions right now, Open Amiga have developed alternative,
contingency plans in order to operate and function without the need for such
close co-operation with Amiga Incorporated. This has the advantage of our being
able to operate independently and without concerning Amiga with a stream of
requests and questions, but has the disadvantage that we are not able to
fine-tune our projects and our plans in sync with those of Amiga, or to plan in
co-operation with Amiga Incorporated, but these issues can always be addressed
at a later time.

In short, we intend to keep up the momentum we have built up, and to continue to
aggressively pursue and implement our own product plans and strategies to create
a successful, free, portable Amiga operating system clone which is hardware
agnostic and will function on under a variety of CPUs and operating
environments.

In this context, support and mutual co-operation with Amiga is seen as a
desirable element that could be of benefit to both groups, but in no way a
necessity. With access to Gateway's Amiga patents, we are able to operate
independently and pursue our strategies. When Amiga's time frees up a little, we
look forward to further discussing our plans with them and to working together
with them. In the meantime, we proceed with developing our products and plans
independently of Amiga.

           The Free Software Foundation and the Open Amiga Foundation

As an organisation that marries the interests of the free-software and Amiga
communities, the Open Amiga Foundation is in contact with Richard Stallman of
the Free Software Foundation, to explore options to address issues of mutual
concern and interest.

Discussions with Mr. Stallman are still at an early stage and it is too early to
comment on what may come of this, but we are hopeful that we will be able to
reach a level of understanding and of co-operation that will benefit both the
Free Software and Amiga communities, and bring mutual benefits to both the GNU
and AROS development projects.

Open Amiga is committed to seeking alliances and strategic relationships with
organisations (whether for-profit or nonprofit) that share a common interest in
the direction we are pursueing and the activities we are undertaking, from the
Amiga, Open Source, Free Software and general, mainstream business world, trying
our best to bring the Amiga into the mainstream of modern computing, without
losing our unique identity in the process.

We encourage people who work for Amiga or Free Software organisations and
businesses with an interest in our activities, or who may have business
proposals for us, to contact us. We are interested in seeking alliances with
organisations wherever this is mutual gain in doing so.

Open Amiga and AROS remain committed to a future where the AmigaOS will remain
an independent and sovereign operating system, available for a wide variety of
software and hardware platforms, operating environments and CPUs, with all the
functionality, appearance, power and flexibility of the original AmigaOS - with
added new, modern features being implemented in the process.

                             Work Continues on AROS

The AROS project, which is at the heart of it all, continues to gain momentum
and support from more Amiga developers, but we still need your help. If you are
a developer and you support our work, what are you waiting for? E-mail Aaron
Digulla and ask to be added to the AROS Developers list, the heat of the action
for development on the AmigaOS/AROS project.

Open Amiga is working on a progress report section on our website to track the
latest developments of the AROS project. It should be going online the same time
as the rest of the website.

                Open Amiga Foundation About To Spread It's Wings

The Open Amiga Foundation came one step closer today to being a legally
registered entity. In order words, the Open Amiga Foundation will soon be born -
officially.

We today proudly posted the result of several weeks of work, in the form of
several sheets of legalese - our completed Memorandum and Articles of
Association, Form 10, Form 12, and Form 30(5)c to Companies House.

This is part of the formal process of turning Open Amiga into a legally
registered nonprofit limited company. This status will be useful in our
negotiations with other companies, and offers certain advantages that will be
helpful in carrying on business. Companies will also have a clear contact for
any commercial matters they may wish to discuss.

We will also be able to ask for and receive gifts and donations. Companies and
individuals who support our work and would like to see AROS developed quicker
will be able to donate money or hardware to the project to speed things along.
There are also a variety of cost-free things people will be able to do to help
us in our projects. More information on this will be available on our website,
when it goes online, when we're registered :)

Once we receive our Certificate of Incorporation, the new Open Amiga Foundation
website will go online, and this will be the official birth of the Open Amiga
Foundation. Then the real fun begins! (As well as plenty more hard work!)

                           Your Feedback and Comments

Again, your comments and feedback are central to our work. We strive to be the
best embodiment of the ideas, inspirations and collective creative talent of the
Amiga community that we possibly can. Open Amiga and AROS would not exist
without the hard work and dedication of a great number of grassroots Amiga users
and developers, and it's thanks to all of the dedicated hard work and talent of
people like you, that this project has been possible, and there is plenty more
to come.

In order to better serve the Amiga community, we need your comments, thoughts,
suggestions and feedback. Please use the contact information below to share your
thoughts with us. We'd love to hear from you.

You can e-mail us at president@amigakernel.org, use ICQ number 21722511 to send
us an online message (checked daily), or phone our company headquarters on +44
(0)1778 393323 between 9am and 9pm GMT to speak directly with our president,
Steve Crietzman. (Unlike many groups, we actually encourage direct communication
wherever possible, so please do not hestitate to call or ICQ.)

Thank you again for your continued interest and support of the Open Amiga
Foundation / AROS. We appreciate your kind e-mails of support, please keep them
coming! :)

We'll continue to do our part, in doing deals and forming relationships, and
continuing to develop great, free software for the good of the Amiga community!

AmigaOS still has plenty of life and potential left in it. With your help, we
can really help push back the boundaries and have it fight it's corner and
establish a niche in the mainstream of modern computing.

Best regards,

Steve Crietzman
President and CEO
Open Amiga Foundation
